    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Horizontal members connecting and supporting the legs of furniture in an X-form. This form is of Italian origin, often having a scrolled or serpentine figure with a finial in the center. Introduced into England toward the end of the 17th century.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000009641/Comstock, American Furniture (1962)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079629/Schwartz, 19th Century America: Furniture and Other Decorative Arts (1970)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Horizontale Verbindungselemente die Beine von Möbeln in einer X-Form verbinden und unterstützen. Diese Form ist italienischer Herkunft, oft in gerollter oder gewundener Form, oftmals mit einem Abschluss in der Mitte. In England gegen Ende des 17. Jahrhunderts eingeführt.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
